<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="72" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[227,348,980,1006]" box="[227,348,980,1006]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,348,980,1006]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,348,980,1006]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[227,1436,1027,1125]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">
Species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hyatt" authorityYear="1893" box="[355,472,1028,1053]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[355,472,1028,1053]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Rineceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with weakly depressed, rounded-trapezoidal whorl profile (ww/wh ~1.45), venter slightly flattened, ventrolateral shoulder broadly rounded. Whorls not embracing. Ornament with a few spiral lines on the flank and the venter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[227,1390,1164,1238]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[227,362,1164,1190]" box="[227,362,1164,1190]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,362,1164,1190]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,362,1164,1190]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[227,1390,1211,1238]" box="[227,1390,1211,1238]" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">
From the Latin ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[420,516,1212,1237]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Rineceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="5" pageNumber="72" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenerum">
<emphasis box="[420,516,1212,1237]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="72">tenerum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, meaning ‘tender’ and referring to the comparatively delicate spiral lines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
